document.title: Grades K-12 Computer Science Performance Standards

30C39FB551E0420BA27C0D5DBA382FAC.description: Continue to discuss and understand the implications of positive and negative digital footprints and that they never go away.

5641A9FB4A9B4EC89225630607CC1F7A.description: Observe intellectual property rights and give appropriate credit when using resources.

6D57891C2739492B8D22FB8197CAEDA8.description: Develop a code of conduct, explain and practice grade-level appropriate behavior and responsibilities while participating in an online community (e.g., talking safely online, promoting good digital citizens, privacy settings, cyberbullying). Identify and report inappropriate behavior and know how to report cyberbullying.

F197932312B14BDAA67038BE769E6435.description: Develop a code of conduct, explain and practice grade-level appropriate behavior and responsibilities while participating in an online community (e.g., using strong passwords, creating a positive online community, recognizing spam and what to do about it, citing online sources). Identify and report inappropriate behavior and know how to report cyberbullying.

3EB8610B8E664113B5DEABA42D0399D4.description: Develop a code of conduct, explain and practice grade-level appropriate behavior and responsibilities while participating in an online community (e.g., responsibilities of being a good digital citizen, private and personal information, showing respect for other people's work). Identify and report inappropriate behavior and know how to report cyberbullying.

D22F6B78D6B34245B815446BBB73B196.description: Develop, test and refine digital artifacts to improve accessibility and usability.

CF1E3B90E86F4E8F8021DC1CDC25751A.description: Create a program using control structures (e.g., sequence, conditionals, interactive-looping), event handlers and variables to solve a problem or express ideas both independently and collaboratively.

or propose cause and effect relationships,
predict outcomes or communicate an
idea.

4D9347BE01DD4E12BAE01745A4D05D53.description: Determine how the accuracy of conclusions are influenced by the amount of useful and reliable data collected.

3D7210A5FE28462B97FD886192CD3E00.description: With guidance, utilize data to make predictions and discuss whether there is adequate data to be useful and to make reliable predictions.

87A197D7495C4EFD99B209AAA689C76A.description: Organize and present collected data to highlight comparisons and support a claim.

EB571CA257E04BCFABCBF255CED7BEA7.description: Organize and present collected data visually to highlight comparisons.

CDCE028ABB9B4D56B84B10AE9DE69746.description: Collect data using various programs and formats (e.g., surveys, forms) and organize the data in various visual formats (e.g., charts, graphs, tables).

67D9F3A5C6A14621826533A22932F5BD.description: Evaluate trade-offs, including availability and quality, based on the type of file, storage requirements (e.g., file size, availability, available memory) and sharing requirements.

CFAAC9CA25BB4605BC7CC64684F98939.description: Choose different storage locations (e.g., physical, shared, cloud) based on the type of file, storage requirements (e.g., file size, availability, available memory) and sharing requirements.

D8BE69C55AC1444CBEC4F516DA22B45C.description: Recognize that different types of information are stored in different formats that have associated programs (e.g., documents open in a word processor) and varied storage requirements.

093A459E90E44D81A06885E9BB7A7499.description: Discuss cybersecurity problems caused by information that is published for different reasons (e.g., inform, advertise, persuade, harm)

1003CF8165C6432C92F85046B134DD22.description: Analyze the credibility of digital information (e.g., comparing multiple accounts and sources, the author's point of view).

81B9EFAF4153469B843B567D1F67A991.description: Discuss real-world cybersecurity problems and identify strategies for how personal information can be protected.

9C9F14AC18794F9FBD9D4C7A3D4D7B95.description: Identify problems that relate to inappropriate use of computing devices and networks.

FF25A6157F01453FA5FE9AF1420CEAB2.description: Model how information is broken down into packets, transmitted through multiple computing devices over networks and the internet and reassembled at the destination.

CD998C757A4544589F14DCFE051FA561.description: Explain how information is broken down into packets, transmitted through multiple computing devices over networks and the internet and reassembled at the destination.

FF676EB72D8E46C5B7A370C56FBC4BC3.description:
Recognize how information
changes when sent and received over
physical or wireless paths. (Information is
broken into smaller parts, sent to the
destination and then reassembled into a
whole.)

95535CB0C8FD4B248E5E285418D4EF50.description: Identify, using accurate terminology, simple hardware and software problems that may occur during everyday use. Discuss problems with peers and adults, apply strategies for solving these problems and explain why the strategy should work.

E0093D9C174549838DA5C8AFB7C39F29.description: Identify, using accurate terminology, simple hardware and software problems that may occur during everyday use, discuss problems with peers and adults and apply strategies for solving these problems (e.g., rebooting the computing device, checking the power, force shut down of an application).

265514407C6C4372B06C23060E32095D.description: Identify, using accurate terminology, simple hardware and software problems that may occur during everyday use, discuss problems with peers and adults and apply strategies for solving these problems (e.g., refresh the screen, closing and reopening an application or file, unmuting or adjusting the volume on headphones).

A42ECD26426543E2A5835C5857DAB38A.description: Model that information is translated, transmitted and processed in order to flow through hardware and software.
